@Bartolomeus-649 

> As a last step, when no other function, cmdLet, application or whatever is found, then use the regEx on the potential command and see if it match.\

You should be able to implement this (or at least prototype it) in PowerShell as is using the `CommandNotFoundAction`  . Here's an (old) example I wrote to do autoloading in PowerShell (this was before we added it natively.)

```powershell

$executioncontext.InvokeCommand.CommandNotFoundAction = {
    $ModuleTable = Get-ModuleAutoLoadData
    $commandName = $_.CommandName
    $moduleName = $ModuleTable[$commandName]
    if ($moduleName)
    {
        $mod = Import-Module -Name $moduleName -PassThru
        $cmd = $mod.ExportedCommands[$commandName]
        if ($cmd)
        {
            $_.Command = $cmd
            $_.StopSearch = $true
        }
    }
}
```

I was thinking something much more generic, not just for dates.

The regex defines how parameters should be extracted from the function name.

Another example

This would allow you to write `RcdGcdBcd` and get back :
```
ColorContext :
A            : 255
R            : 205
G            : 205
B            : 205
ScA          : 1
ScR          : 0.6104956
ScG          : 0.6104956
ScB          : 0.6104956

```
```
function /R(?<red>\d{3}|[0-9a-f]{2})G(?<green>\d{1,3}|[0-9a-f]{2})B(?<blue>\d{1,3}|[0-9a-f]{2})/([string]$red, $green, $blue)
{
    [byte]$redInt;
    [byte]$greenInt;
    [byte]$bleuInt;

    if($red.Length -eq 3)
    {
        $redInt =  [Int64]::Parse($red, [System.Globalization.NumberStyles]::HexNumber);
        $blueInt =  [Int64]::Parse($blue, [System.Globalization.NumberStyles]::HexNumber);
        $bleInt =  [Int64]::Parse($green, [System.Globalization.NumberStyles]::HexNumber);
    }
    else
   {
        $redInt =  [Int64]::Parse($red);
        $blueInt =  [Int64]::Parse($blue);
        $bleInt =  [Int64]::Parse($green);        
   }

    return [System.Windows.Media.Color]::FromRgb($redInt, $greenInt, $blueInt);
}

```

The main point is you should be able to use it inline just about anywhere, without any parentheses, arguments and other stuff that take up space and lowers readability. 

Also, they should be deterministic and [100% pure functions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pure_function) .

I managed to get some kind of proof of concept/prototype based on the code provided by @BrucePay .
Not sure if it's the right way to go about creating dynamic functions, but at least it works for one dynamic function at a time.

with this you can now write command like these, without there existing none of the "Ago-functions":
```
Get-EventLog -LogName System -After (4hAgo)
Get-EventLog -LogName System -After (1wAgo)
Get-EventLog -LogName System -After (1dAgo)

```


